{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"513110f2-3068-4d64-93a0-89060ab4e3c4","content":"Yes, both are known MSTest v4 breaking changes. Here's a summary:\n\n---\n\n### 1. Lost test history in Azure DevOps\n\nMSTest v4 changed the **test-ID generation strategy**. The default is now `FullyQualifiedName` instead of the v3 `DisplayName`-based ID. Azure DevOps tracks tests by ID, so every test looks new.\n\n**Fix** — add to your `.runsettings`:\n\n```xml\n<MSTest>\n  <TestIdGenerationStrategy>DisplayName</TestIdGenerationStrategy>\n</MSTest>\n```\n\nOr if you want to adopt the new IDs, just accept the one-time history break.\n\n---\n\n### 2. `TestContext.TestName` in `[ClassInitialize]`\n\nIn v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is a **class-level context** — it's no longer tied to a specific test. Accessing `TestName` (or other test-scoped properties) throws `InvalidOperationException`.\n\nYour code on **line 13** hits this:\n\n```csharp\nvar testName = context.TestName; // 💥 throws in v4\n```\n\n**Fix** — remove or guard the access, since class init runs once *before* any test:\n\n```csharp\n[ClassInitialize]\npublic static void ClassInit(TestContext context)\n{\n    // context.TestName is not available here in v4.\n    // Use context.FullyQualifiedTestClassName if you need the class name.\n}\n```\n\nIf you need per-test setup logic, move it to `[TestInitialize]` where `TestContext` is fully populated.\n\n---\n\n### 3. Other v4 changes to watch out for\n\n| Area | What changed |\n|---|---|\n| **`[ClassInitialize]`/`[ClassCleanup]` inheritance** | Now default to `InheritanceBehavior.BeforeEachDerivedClass` / `…AfterEachDerivedClass`. If you relied on the v3 default (`None`), base-class init may now run for derived classes unexpectedly. Set `[ClassInitialize(InheritanceBehavior.None)]` explicitly to keep old behavior. |\n| **`TestContext.Properties`** | Now read-only in class/assembly-level contexts. Writes that worked in v3 may throw. |\n| **Parallel execution defaults** | v4 enables method-level parallelism more aggressively. Tests with shared static state may start failing intermittently. Control with `[assembly: Parallelize(Scope = ExecutionScope.ClassLevel)]` or disable entirely. |\n| **`Assert.AreEqual` on doubles** | Floating-point overloads are stricter about tolerance. Tests comparing `double` without a delta may fail. |\n| **Removed obsolete APIs** | Several long-deprecated members (e.g., some `DataSource` attributes) were removed. If you had warnings in v3, they're now errors. |\n\nAny of these ringing a bell for your project? I can help fix specific cases.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"71ea611e-1863-481c-953d-a935389c6420","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user has upgraded to MSTest v4 and is asking about known breaking changes. Let me provide a comprehensive answer about the key MSTest v4 changes that affect them.\n\nKey MSTest v4 breaking changes I know about:\n\n1. **Fully qualified test ID (FQTID)**: MSTest v4 changed the default test ID format to use fully qualified names. This is why all tests appear as \"new\" in Azure DevOps - the test IDs changed. The workaround is to set `<TestIdGenerationStrategy>DisplayName</TestIdGenerationStrategy>` in the .runsettings file or project properties to restore the old behavior.\n\n\n2. **TestContext in ClassInitialize**: The `TestContext` parameter in `[ClassInitialize]` methods no longer has an associated test, so accessing `TestContext.TestName` will throw or return null since class initialization runs before any individual test executes.\n3. There are also changes to how `[ClassInitialize]` and `[ClassCleanup]` inheritance works, `TestContext.Properties` read-only behavior in certain scenarios, potential timeout adjustments, and shifts in how assembly-level attributes function.","outputTokens":1055,"requestId":"0C03:2A854:B310D9:CF2F32:69F023F7"},"id":"51f8d717-a49c-4797-9af9-e5c6ef1db0da","timestamp":"2026-04-28T03:05:51.875Z","parentId":"f4cc59da-1c18-49a5-bde7-f80fdcb58db6"}
